# github actions==CI/CD pipelineing tool

## CI = continuous integration
Continuous Integration (CI) means:
Developers frequently merge code into a shared repository, and every change is automatically built and tested.

ğŸ”¥ What happens in CI?
When you push code to GitHub:
âœ… Code is pulled
âœ… Dependencies are installed
âœ… Tests are executed
âœ… Build is created (e.g., Docker image)
âŒ If tests fail â†’ pipeline fails

ğŸ¯ Goal of CI: Catch bugs early before we do the merge.
ğŸ¯ CI does:  Push â†’ Run tests â†’ Build Docker image â†’ Push to Docker Hub



## CD = continous deployment  (or Continuous Delivery)
There are two meanings people confuse:
1ï¸âƒ£ Continuous Delivery- build+test+approval to deploy
Code is automatically prepared for release,but manual approval is needed to deploy.
2ï¸âƒ£ Continuous Deployment -build+test+deploy
Code is automatically deployed to production without manual approval.

ğŸ¯ CD does:New Docker image â†’ Deploy to Kubernetes cluster automatically


ğŸ¯ CI/CD -pipleline is managed by github actions -and github action is the tool used to build , test , deploy the application automatically.


## Workflow file in github action
- A Workflow in GitHub Actions:
âœ… It is a YAML (.yml) file
âœ… Contains automation instructions for your project
âœ… Stored inside: .github/workflows/your-file.yml

- It defines:
When to run (Events)
What to run (Jobs)
How to run (Steps)

## Events/triggres:
- triggres are used to run the yml Triggers define when the workflow should run.
- Common triggers:
on:
  push:    -- When code is pushed
  pull_request:   --- When PR is created/updated
  workflow_dispatch:   --- Manual trigger
  schedule:     ---Runs on cron schedule

## JOB:
A Job:
- Is a group of steps
- Runs on a machine
- That machine is called a Runner
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

ğŸ–¥ Runner
- Runner = Machine where job executes
- Types: ubuntu-latest , windows-latest , macos-latest

## steps:
- A Job is divided into Steps.
- Each step performs a small task like:
   -- Checkout code
   -- Install Python
   -- Install dependencies
   -- Run tests 
   -- Build Docker image

ğŸ”¥ Final Structure
Workflow
   â”œâ”€â”€ Events (Triggers)
   â”œâ”€â”€ Jobs
          â”œâ”€â”€ Runner
          â”œâ”€â”€ Steps


# variables in github actions
1.workflow variabls
  - These are defined inside the workflow .yml file.
  - Can be defined at:- Workflow level , Job level , Step level
2.configurations variables
  - These are stored inside GitHub settings.
3.secret
  - Used for:Passwords , API keys , Docker credentials , Cloud tokens
4.Context variables
  - These are predefined variables provided by GitHub.

# making self runner
- mkdir actions-runner; cd actions-runner

- Invoke-WebRequest -Uri https://github.com/actions/runner/releases/download/v2.331.0/actions-runner-win-x64-2.331.0.zip -OutFile actions-runner-win-x64-2.331.0.zip


-if((Get-FileHash -Path actions-runner-win-x64-2.331.0.zip -Algorithm SHA256).Hash.ToUpper() -ne '473e74b86cd826e073f1c1f2c004d3fb9e6c9665d0d51710a23e5084a601c78a'.ToUpper()){ throw 'Computed checksum did not match' }

- Add-Type -AssemblyName System.IO.Compression.FileSystem ; [System.IO.Compression.ZipFile]::ExtractToDirectory("$PWD/actions-runner-win-x64-2.331.0.zip", "$PWD")

// config
- ./config.cmd --url https://github.com/Prakhar17m/Github-ACTIONS --token A7KUJVH2YIAZSNLD56KQKFDJSHH6M

